I noticed at the in the new AssetManager class that bitmaps are decoded asynchronously based on the imageDecodingPolicy set on the loader, however ATF textures do not seem to be affected by that setting. The async setting for ATF textures is on the "fromAtfData" method.

In the AssetManager class in the method "onUrlLoaderComplete" in the switch case under the case for ATF there is a function call for "addTexture". After addTexture there is a call to onComplete, I moved that onComplete function to the last parameter of the addTexture function to enable async loading for ATF files loaded by url. Something similar would need to be for ATF loaded from embedded assets.

```
case "atf":
   addTexture(name, Texture.fromAtfData(bytes, mScaleFactor, mUseMipMaps, onComplete));
   //onComplete();
   break;
```

It seems to work well so far, any thoughts on problems this might cause? or other things to consider?

I'm using a sprite that contains a movieclip.
However, it seems like scaling the sprite (using scaleX, scaleY) affects the visible size of the child movieclip but _not_ it's width property:

``` actionscript
public class Asteroid extends Sprite
{
  image = new MovieClip(Assets.getTextureAtlas().getTextures("texturename"));
  addChild(image);
  trace(this.width,image.width, this.scaleX, this.scaleY);
  // output - 26,26,1,1

  this.scaleX = this.scaleY = 0.5
  trace(this.width,image.width, this.scaleX, this.scaleY);
  // output - 13,26,0.5,0.5
  // notice how the image width after scaling stays 26
  // visibly the image is scaled to half it's size though
}
```

I'm dynamically changing the fps of many MovieClips and it proving to be quite a bottle neck

_(Project is a nature / tree simulation, eg. each leaf is a MovieClip slightly flapping in the wind, with more life like movement being achieved by altering the fps of each leaf periodically)_

It appears that the looped setFrameDuration calls and its subsequent calls to updateStartTimes are doing too many loops that they don't need to be.

Below is optimised version i'm using that solves the problem. 

I have inlined the setFrameDuration call and call updateStartTimes only once.  

Doing so dropped the expense of the fps calls from 54% of frame time to 4% (in Adobe Scout)

```
public function set fps(value:Number):void
        {
            if (value <= 0) throw new ArgumentError("Invalid fps: " + value);

          var newFrameDuration:Number = 1.0 / value;
            var acceleration:Number = newFrameDuration / mDefaultFrameDuration;
            mCurrentTime *= acceleration;
            mDefaultFrameDuration = newFrameDuration;

            var duration:Number = mDurations[i] * acceleration;

            for (var i:int=0; i<numFrames; ++i) {
                // setFrameDuration(i, mDurations[i] * acceleration);
        // **Inlined and optimised setFrameDuration below
                mTotalTime -= mDurations[i];
        mTotalTime += duration;
            mDurations[i] = duration;
        }

            updateStartTimes(); // **Now just called once instead * numFrames
        }
```

HTH & Cheers for this great framework.

Hi,
i've added .pex support without that AssetManager needs to know the Particle-System extension.
In practice just put your particle assets to assets/particles/{0}x directories and enque it with
assets.enqueue(...,
              appDir.resolvePath(formatString("particles/{0}x", scaleFactor))
              );

In the class that wants to add a particle extension just write
_fullExplosion = new PDParticleSystem(Game.assets.getParticleConfig("YourExplosion"), Game.assets.getTexture("YourExplosion"));
addChild(_fullExplosion);

and it works. No embedding of textures or .pex files needed anymore.

I hope that you can use it.
Best regards
Valentin

